<p>The <code>trim</code> function removes whitespace from the beginning and end of a string.</p>

<h2>Basic Usage</h2>
<pre>{open}echo $spacedText | trim{close}</pre>
<p>Result: <b>{echo $spacedText | trim}</b></p>

<h2>Leading/Trailing Spaces</h2>
<pre>{open}echo '  hello  ' | trim{close}</pre>
<p>Trimmed: <b>[{echo '  hello  ' | trim}]</b></p>

<h2>Newlines and Tabs</h2>
<pre>{open}echo '
  text
' | trim{close}</pre>
<p>Clean: <b>{echo '
  text
' | trim}</b></p>

<h2>Chained Examples</h2>
<pre>{open}echo $spacedText | trim | upper{close}</pre>
<p>Trimmed and uppercase: <b>{echo $spacedText | trim | upper}</b></p>

<pre>{open}echo '  john smith  ' | trim | capitalize{close}</pre>
<p>Clean name: <b>{echo '  john smith  ' | trim | capitalize}</b></p>

<pre>{open}echo $email | trim | lower{close}</pre>
<p>Normalized email: <b>{echo $email | trim | lower}</b></p>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>Trim only removes whitespace from edges, not from within the string. Use <code>white</code> to normalize internal spaces.</p>
